<details><summary><i>Previously, dgquintas (David G. Quintas) wroteâ€¦</i></summary><blockquote>

No. We don't care about sorting order in this case. And even if we did, the only consequence is that the "sorted" result would cluster equal elements together. 

There's no simple way to define a comparison between tables. Even if we wanted to (something we don't currently need), it'd necessitate adding extra methods to the slice_hash_table API, for more (unnecessary) complexity.
</blockquote></details>

The channel_args vtable uses a cmp function, not an equality function, which implies that it does actually care about sorting.  Even if there's no code that currently does sorting, if someone were to add that later, they would look at this vtable, see the cmp function, and assume that they already have what they need to do sorting.  Given that, I think we should be consistent here.

I don't think there's any significant increased complexity here.  We're already adding a bunch of "equals" methods; all we need to do is make them "cmp" methods instead.

