I don't think there's anything stopping someone from using an empty slice as a real key, in which case this might falsely compare as equal when it shouldn't.  I suggest explicitly checking whether the entries are empty first (which I think is also a bit clearer to read):

```
if (is_empty(&a->entries[i])) {
  if (!is_empty(&b->entries[i])) {
    return -1;  // a empty but b non-empty
  }
  continue;  // both empty, no need to check key or value
} else if (is_empty(&b->entries[i])) {
  return 1;  // a non-empty but b empty
}
// neither empty
const int key_cmp = grpc_slice_cmp(a->entries[i].key, b->entries[i].key);
if (key_cmp != 0) return key_cmp;
const int value_cmp = value_cmp_fn_a(a->entries[i].value, b->entries[i].value);
if (value_cmp != 0) return value_cmp;
```

